otiating Murder in the Historiae of Gregory of Tours -- t14 Poisoning, Killing and Murder in the Edictus Rothari -- t15 Murder, Foul and Fair, in Shota Rustaveli’s The Man in the Panther Skin -- t16 A Multiple Poisoning in the City of Valencia: Sanxo Calbó’s Crime (1442) -- t17 A Case of Mariticide in Late Medieval France -- t18 Monstrous Un-Making: Maternal Infanticide and Female Agency in Early Modern England -- t19 Imps of Hell: Young People, Murder and the Early English Press -- tConclusion -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDrawing on a wealth of sources from different disciplines, the essays here provide a nuanced picture of how medieval and early modern societies viewed murder and dealt with murderers.Murder - the perpetrators, victims, methods and motives - has been the subject of law, literature, chronicles and religion, often crossing genres and disciplines and employing multiple modes of expression and interpretation. As the chapters in this volume demonstrate, definitions of murder, manslaughter and justified or unjustified homicide depend largely on the legal terminology and the laws of the society. Much like modern nations, medieval societies treated murder and murderers differently based on their social standing, the social standing of the victim, their gender, their mental capacity for understanding their crime, and intent, motive and means. The three parts of this volume explore different aspects of this crime in the Middle Ages. The first provides the legal template for reading cases of murder in a variety of sources. The second examines the public hermeneutics of murder, especially theways in which medieval societies interpreted and contextualised their textual traditions: Icelandic sagas, Old French fabliaux, Arthuriana and accounts of assassination. Finally, the third part focuses on the effects of murder within the community: murder as a social ill, especially in killing kin. LARISSA TRACY is Professor of Medieval Literature at Longwood University. Contributors: Dianne Berg, G. Koolemans Beynen, Dwayne C. Coleman, Jeffrey Doolittle, Carmel Ferragud, Jay Paul Gates, Thomas Gobbitt, Emily J. Hutchison, Jolanta N. Komornicka, Anne Latowsky, Matthew Lubin, Andrew McKenzie-McHarg, Ben Parsons, Ilse Schweitzer VanDonkelaar, Hannah Skoda, Bridgette Slavin, Larissa Tracy, Patricia Turning, Lucas Wood  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aMurderxHistoryy16th century. 0aMurderxHistoryy17th century. 0aMurderxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCrime.  aEarly Modern Murder.  aHistorical Contexts.  aHomicide.  aInterpretation.  aLegal Contexts.  aLiterary Contexts.  aMedieval Manuscripts.  aMedieval Murder.  aSociety.  amedieval.1 aBerg, Dianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeynen, G. Koolemans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Dwayne C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Dwayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoolittle, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerragud, Carmel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGates, Jay Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGobbitt, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Emily J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchison, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKomornicka, Jolanta N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat